        "title": "Modelo SIR para compreender epidemias",
        "excerpt":"O modelo SIR apesar de suas limitações auxilia na compreensão do funcionamento de um processo epidemiológico. Nesse trabalho podemos determinar uma solução analítica para o sistema de equações que caracterizam tal modelo. Ainda, usando conceitos de regressão linear por mínimos quadrados, podemos sugerir uma maneira de se obter as constantes $\\beta$ e $\\gamma$ que compoem a definição do número básico de reprodução $R_0$.   Modelo SIR   O modelo SIR é assim denominado por considerar uma partição de uma população sujeita a uma infecção viral em $3$ (três) grupos: suscetíveis, infectados e Removidos. O grupo dos indivíduos que constituem os removidos é considerado aqui como a junção de indivíduos, que após serem infectados, foram a óbito ou que se recuperaram da enfermidade e se tornam imunes. O grupo dos suscetíveis é constituído por indivíduos que ainda não estão imunes a contaminação e, portanto, podem se infectar.   \\centering {width=”50%”}   Some examples to get started   How to add Comments   Comments can be added to your project by clicking on the comment icon in the toolbar above.   To reply to a comment, simply click the reply button in the lower right corner of the comment, and you can close them when you’re done.   How to include Figures   First you have to upload the image file from your computer using the upload link the project menu. Then use the includegraphics command to include it in your document. Use the figure environment and the caption command to add a number and a caption to your figure. See the code for Figure [fig:frog]{reference-type=”ref” reference=”fig:frog”} in this section for an example.   \\centering {width=”30%”}   How to add Tables   Use the table and tabular commands for basic tables — see Table [tab:widgets]{reference-type=”ref” reference=”tab:widgets”}, for example.      \\centering     Item        Quantity     ——— ———-     Widgets           42     Gadgets           13        [[tab:widgets]]{#tab:widgets label=”tab:widgets”}An example table.       How to write Mathematics   LaTeX is great at typesetting mathematics. Let $X_1, X_2, \\ldots, X_n$ be a sequence of independent and identically distributed random variables with $\\text{E}[X_i] = \\mu$ and $\\text{Var}[X_i] = \\sigma^2 &lt; \\infty$, and let  denote their mean. Then as $n$ approaches infinity, the random variables $\\sqrt{n}(S_n - \\mu)$ converge in distribution to a normal $\\mathcal{N}(0, \\sigma^2)$.   How to create Sections and Subsections   Use section and subsections to organize your document. Simply use the section and subsection buttons in the toolbar to create them, and we’ll handle all the formatting and numbering automatically.   How to add Lists   You can make lists with automatic numbering …           Like this,            and like this.       …or bullet points …           Like this,            and like this.       How to add Citations and a References List   You can upload a .bib file containing your BibTeX entries, created with JabRef; or import your Mendeley, CiteULike or Zotero library as a .bib file. You can then cite entries from it, like this: [@greenwade93]. Just remember to specify a bibliography style, as well as the filename of the .bib.   You can find a video tutorial here to learn more about BibTeX.   We hope you find Overleaf useful, and please let us know if you have any feedback using the help menu above — or use the contact form at https://www.overleaf.com/contact!   \\bibliographystyle{alpha}     ","categories": [],
